properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system tracking through Saskatchewan will bring 10 or more centimetres of snow to the Prince Albert region Monday. Areas in the Martensville region including the City of Saskatoon are also likely to see 5 to 10 cm of wet snow Monday. The low pressure system will continue towards Manitoba during the day Monday and this snowfall warning may be extended eastward accordingly. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Continued For The Red River Between Emerson And The Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River between Emerson and the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2020-04-07T11:45:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2020-04-06T11:52:17-05:00, 6D3A7836-6547-D5C7-4C7D-823796F6689A
Area: The Red River from Emerson to the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system from Montana is spreading an area of snow and freezing rain through parts of southwestern Saskatchewan this morning. At this time, radar imagery suggests the area of freezing rain will stay mainly west of the city of Moose Jaw. The freezing rain will end this morning but surfaces will remain an icy hazard until temperatures warm above zero. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system moving through Saskatchewan today will arrive in central Manitoba this evening. Heavy snow will begin in areas near the Saskatchewan later this afternoon and spread northeastward throughout the night. There will be a rapid accumulation of 10 to 15 cm of snow as the this weather system moves through the area. Poor visibilities in falling snow will affect travel. The snowfall will taper off tonight or early Tuesday as this system continues towards Ontario. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system from Montana will track through southern Saskatchewan today. This weather system is bringing wintery weather through much of southwestern Saskatchewan. A swath of heavy snow will push through the region giving a quick snowfall accumulation of 10 to 15 cm. Visibilities will be very low in the falling snow and travel will be affected. Even though heavy snowfall accumulations are not forecast for regions towards the Alberta border, there will be periods of very low visibilities in falling snow this morning. The weather system will move through the northeastern grainbelt this afternoon bringing with it the heavy snow. At the same the heavy snowfall will be weakening in more western areas. The heavy snowfall will push entirely out of Saskatchewan and into Manitoba this evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2020-04-07T02:34:52-00:00
